    scholarsSaid: [
      { scholar: "Ibn al-Qayyim", source: "Madarij al-Salikin", text: "The amanah is the right of Allah upon the human, and the right of the human upon himself, and the right of others upon him. Whoever fulfils all three has fulfilled the trust." },
      { scholar: "Al-Raghib al-Asfahani", source: "Mufradat", text: "Amanah is used for any state whose preservation is required, whether it relates to rights of Allah, rights of people, or the trust between the nafs and itself." },
      { scholar: "Ibn Kathir", source: "Tafsir Ibn Kathir on 33:72", text: "The amanah here refers to acts of obedience with their specific conditions of obligation and the consequences of violation — rewards and punishment. The human undertook to carry this, and Allah tested him." },
    ],
    hadith: [
      { text: "When the trust is lost, await the Hour. It was asked: How will it be lost? He said: When authority is given to those who do not deserve it.", source: "Sahih al-Bukhari" },
      { text: "There is no faith in one who is not trustworthy, and there is no religion in one who does not keep his promises.", source: "Musnad Ahmad" },
    ],
    acrossTransitions: "In the Sufi tradition, amanah becomes the great paradox of human existence: the human is the only creature in creation who can sin — and the only creature who can repent. The angels cannot fall; the animals do not choose. The human alone holds a trust that can be broken, and for that reason alone, holds a dignity no other creation shares.\n\nIn Islamic jurisprudence, amanah structures an entire category of legal relationships — wadi'ah (deposits), wakalah (agency), and ijara (employment) are all built on the framework of trust. The person entrusted with something is called the amin, and their liability is limited by the conditions of the trust — unless they transgress.\n\nAcross the ethical tradition, the Prophet ﷺ is described as al-Amin — the Trustworthy — even before prophethood. He was given that name by Quraysh who had no reason to call him so except that experience had demonstrated it beyond doubt. Trustworthiness precedes the message; it is its first proof.",
