    acrossTransitions: "In Islamic architecture, the dunya found its most eloquent expression in the garden — the riyad, the courtyard with flowing water and fruit trees — which deliberately echoed Quranic descriptions of the akhira. The garden was a reminder: this is what it points to. Beauty is not to be rejected; it is to be read.\n\nIn Sufi poetry, the dunya became the sea of forgetfulness (bahr al-ghafla) or the veil that covers the heart. The mystic's task was to move through the world without drowning in it — to keep one's gaze on the divine horizon even while the hands were in the world's soil.\n\nIn Islamic economics, the prohibition of hoarding, the obligation of zakat, and the ethics of trade all reflect a dunya properly understood: wealth is not yours to accumulate indefinitely, because wealth is an amanah, not a possession. The economic system is built on the theological premise that the dunya belongs ultimately to Allah.",
