    hadith: [
      { text: "The upper hand is better than the lower hand. The upper hand is the one that gives, and the lower hand is the one that receives. Begin with those who are your dependents.", source: "Sahih al-Bukhari and Muslim" },
      { text: "Eat together and do not scatter, for barakah comes with the group.", source: "Sunan Ibn Majah — Hasan" },
    ],
    acrossTransitions: "The geography of barakah is central to Islamic spirituality. The three sacred mosques — in Makkah, Madinah, and Jerusalem — are blessed sites not because of any physical property of their soil, but because of the divine attention that has descended on them. To pray in the Masjid al-Haram is worth a hundred thousand prayers; to pray in the Masjid al-Nabawi is worth a thousand. This quantification is itself a map of barakah — divine blessing distributed unevenly, generously, and purposefully.\n\nThe concept of barakah runs through Islamic economics as a quiet corrective to pure materialism. It suggests that the productivity of an economy is not merely a function of its inputs — it depends on whether its methods, intentions, and distributions are aligned with divine will. Halal income carries barakah; haram income does not, regardless of its quantity.\n\nIn the living tradition, the seeking of barakah from scholars and righteous people reflects the understanding that human beings can become containers of divine overflow — that spending time with the wise, the pious, and the loving is not merely intellectually or emotionally beneficial but spiritually generative. The company of the righteous is itself a form of barakah.",
